11_wave_midline


  1. Question

    A sinusoidal wave is graphed below.


    The midline is at \(y=D\). Find \(D\).


    Solution

    The vertical offset can be found by subtracting the amplitude from the maximum.

    The amplitude of a sinusoidal function is half the difference between the maximum \(y\) and the minimum \(y\).


    \[A~=~\frac{(0.3)-(-4.1)}{2} ~=~ \frac{4.4}{2} ~=~ 2.2\]

    The amplitude is 2.2. Subtract 2.2 from 0.3 (the maximum).

    \[D ~=~ 0.3-2.2\] \[D ~=~ -1.9\]

    This exact function could be plotted with the following algebraic definition: \[y(t) = 2.2 \sin\left(\frac{2\pi}{6.4}(t+3.5)\right)+(-1.9)\]

    The amplitude is 2.2; the period is 6.4; the horizontal shift is left by 3.5; and the midline is \(y=-1.9\).
